s 1500–2000.\n\nThe dynamics reveal that the combination of 20 hunters operating under optimal foraging logic, sexual dimorphism favoring female targeting (lower processing cost of 3 versus 6 for males, with comparable food value), and biennial birth spacing (730 steps) creates an unsustainable harvest pressure. Seasonal environmental constraints (seasonality = 0.8) introduce periodic resource limitations that exacerbate vulnerability during low-population bottlenecks, preventing recovery even when hunting pressure temporarily relaxes due to hunter energy dynamics or spatial displacement.\n\n**Implications for Decision Makers:**\nThe parameter configuration tested results in inevitable extinction across all stochastic replicates, indicating that sustainable coexistence requires intervention. Decision makers should prioritize reducing hunter density below the critical threshold of 20 individuals or extending birth spacing intervals beyond 730 steps to allow demographic recovery. The brief recovery episodes observed suggest that temporary hunting moratoriums could potentially prevent extinction if implemented before populations drop below 5 individuals. Additionally, adjusting the sexual dimorphism parameters to reduce the relative profitability of female harvests may shift hunter selectivity toward males, potentially buffering the reproductive core of the population. The consistent 63-step oscillation period indicates that seasonal protection measures aligned with resource scarcity cycles could provide critical windows for population stabilization."  
